Logs — journalctl and slash-var-log.

systemd ships with its own logging daemon, systemd-journald, and it collects log messages from everything: the kernel, every service, and every user session, all into one structured, binary journal. The tool you use to read that journal is journalctl. The big win over the old approach of tailing eight different log files is that you get one unified log, tagged with metadata, which service, which process ID, what priority, plus genuinely powerful filtering.

Let's go through the filters you'll use. journalctl dash-u, then a service name, shows every entry for just that service. Add dash-f and it follows live, exactly like tail dash-f. dash-dash-since with a phrase like "one hour ago," or "today," limits the time range. dash-p filters by priority; the journal uses syslog levels from zero, emergency, up to seven, debug, so journalctl dash-p err shows errors and everything more severe. dash-b limits to the current boot, and dash-b dash-one shows the previous boot, which is invaluable for diagnosing a crash. And dash-k shows just kernel messages, largely replacing the old dmesg.

Now, an important gotcha: persistent versus volatile. By default, on many distributions, the journal is written to slash-run, which is a temporary, in-memory filesystem, so it's wiped on every reboot. If you want your logs to survive reboots, and you usually do, you create the directory slash-var-log-slash-journal, or set Storage equals persistent in the journald config, and journald starts keeping history. You can cap its size with SystemMaxUse, say one gigabyte, or trim it manually with journalctl dash-dash-vacuum-time.

Finally, don't forget the traditional plain-text logs in slash-var-log; they still matter, because many services write there directly, and rsyslog mirrors the journal into plain files. Know a few by name: slash-var-log-slash-syslog on Debian, or messages on Red Hat, for general system messages; auth-dot-log, or secure on Red Hat, for logins and sudo activity; and the dmesg command for the kernel ring buffer. And growing log files are kept in check by logrotate, configured under slash-etc-slash-logrotate-dot-d, which renames, compresses, and eventually expires old logs, usually triggered once a day by a timer.
